{"questionId":"3586765","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>XY</mi></math> is a semicircular path in the park with centre <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>°</mo></math>. Khemil is standing on the path and Odette’s football is at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>. This is shown in the diagram below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong>diagram not to scale</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/93f6881c7a9be490be2df4e5f8f9c2ea222061fd.png\"></p>\n<p>The length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KX</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>53</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>°</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>°</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find whether Odette or Khemil is closer to the football.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to use sine rule with measurements from triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OKX</mi></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>OX</mi><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>51</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>53</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>OX</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4099</mn><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p>Odette is closer to the football / Khemil is further from the football&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> For the final <em><strong>A1</strong></em> to be awarded <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4099</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>)</mo></math> must be seen. Follow through within question part for final <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for a consistent comparison with their <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OX</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>sketch of triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OXK</mi></math> with vertices, angles and lengths&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/8a74de11411da6d9fc18b6b1418040f8d3959df3.png\"></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>51</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>°</mo></math> is smallest angle in triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OXK</mi></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>opposite side (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OX</mi></math>) is smallest length&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>therefore Odette is closest&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"3586765","referenceCode":"23M.2.SL.TZ2.1d","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find whether Odette or Khemil is closer to the football.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.3—Angles of elevation and depression"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}